WEBVTT

00:05.672 --> 00:08.584
Finding the tone and energy of a movie
in the first scene

00:08.675 --> 00:11.508
is very important.

00:11.595 --> 00:15.258
There are two storylines
in the secret in their eyes,

00:15.349 --> 00:19.308
a love story and a detective story.

00:20.687 --> 00:24.350
They don't function on the same level.

00:24.441 --> 00:29.151
You could say the love story
is the main storyline,

00:29.238 --> 00:33.607
the one that drives the entire movie.

00:33.700 --> 00:39.115
And in musical terms, it's the tone,
the main theme.

00:39.206 --> 00:42.073
The detective story is the trigger.

00:42.167 --> 00:46.911
It doesn't drive the plot,
but rather triggers what happens.

00:47.005 --> 00:51.795
It's the secondary theme in terms
of importance, but the dominant one.

00:51.885 --> 00:55.127
It's the macguffin, as Hitchcock would say.

00:55.222 --> 00:57.463
Here we are in the first scene.

00:57.558 --> 01:02.678
We decided that this scene
had to be about the love story.

01:02.771 --> 01:05.979
It may be the most important moment,
the one he remembers best,

01:06.066 --> 01:09.650
the one that broke him.

01:09.736 --> 01:13.024
It's repeated at the end of the second act,

01:13.115 --> 01:16.949
bringing us into the present.

01:18.287 --> 01:20.869
This scene also had to have characteristics

01:20.956 --> 01:25.165
related to memory,
as both storyline and theme.

01:25.252 --> 01:28.039
Memories start to take shape here.

01:32.551 --> 01:35.167
We can remember a person's eyes,

01:35.262 --> 01:38.220
a person's tone
when they told us something important.

01:38.307 --> 01:42.892
Everything else around us
was like a brush stroke of color

01:42.978 --> 01:44.843
or a blurred movement.

01:44.938 --> 01:48.897
That's kind of the esthetic of this scene.

01:48.984 --> 01:54.195
It's an important scene
because memories start to take shape in it.

01:59.453 --> 02:04.493
We didn't want it to end
at a natural ending point,

02:04.583 --> 02:08.121
but rather to be suddenly interrupted
so we could move on to the story.

02:08.211 --> 02:12.295
This tells us that the author was imagining
or remembering what we just saw.

02:13.675 --> 02:17.133
This sequence of esposito writing

02:17.220 --> 02:19.927
and starting the novel in various ways

02:20.015 --> 02:23.803
is a sort of overture of the movie.

02:23.894 --> 02:29.184
In it, we can touch on all the themes,
storylines, and especially the tones

02:29.274 --> 02:31.390
found within the movie.

02:31.485 --> 02:34.477
The main tone

02:36.198 --> 02:39.281
isn't nostalgic, but rather melancholy.

02:39.368 --> 02:43.361
A romantic tone hovers
over the entire movie.

02:43.455 --> 02:47.994
But there's also... coming in right here

02:48.669 --> 02:53.538
is a tone and storyline
from a memory that is exceedingly

02:56.968 --> 02:59.550
generous in its recollection.

03:00.347 --> 03:04.090
His memories almost seem like commercials.

03:04.184 --> 03:07.347
The highlights, everything is very soft,

03:07.437 --> 03:09.928
lyrical, smiling.

03:10.023 --> 03:15.609
But the character chokes on this memory
and finds it completely ridiculous.

03:15.696 --> 03:20.781
However, the image of this girl,
Liliana coloto, alive,

03:20.867 --> 03:24.610
which is something he can only imagine,
is very present in it.

03:27.666 --> 03:32.786
The other storyline and tone of the movie
come in here.

03:40.303 --> 03:42.715
Please, don't...

03:43.056 --> 03:46.264
Please, please...

03:48.395 --> 03:51.808
We know that this is
a painful memory for him,

03:51.898 --> 03:55.937
that plea he was unable to answer.

03:56.820 --> 04:01.484
In those four minutes,
we introduced all the storylines.

04:01.575 --> 04:04.658
I'm going to talk a lot about
the energy in a film,

04:04.745 --> 04:07.532
the energy curve of the tones.

04:07.622 --> 04:10.159
It's more important to talk about
than the plot,

04:10.250 --> 04:13.583
which you either get or you don't
when you see the movie.

04:13.670 --> 04:16.036
There's no need for us to talk about that.

04:29.060 --> 04:32.268
This is the end of that introduction.

04:35.609 --> 04:37.270
A man and his memory.

04:44.075 --> 04:45.736
A sort of prologue.

04:45.827 --> 04:46.827
I fear

04:46.953 --> 04:49.285
the first act starts here.

04:54.711 --> 04:57.168
The movie could have easily started here.

04:57.255 --> 04:59.792
In terms of the plot,

04:59.883 --> 05:03.751
nothing we saw before this matters

05:03.845 --> 05:08.464
because it will all be explained
and narrated in a linear fashion.

05:08.558 --> 05:11.891
But as viewers,
we are already somewhere else,

05:11.978 --> 05:16.062
especially in terms of tone and energy.

05:16.149 --> 05:22.736
If the movie had started here,
it would've been a more conventional story,

05:22.823 --> 05:27.487
and we would've been required
to participate in the movie

05:27.577 --> 05:30.068
in a much more conventional manner,

05:30.163 --> 05:34.497
without emotional or energetic involvement.

05:34.626 --> 05:36.833
The gates have opened.

05:38.046 --> 05:42.790
One of the major decisions in the movie
was how to treat the past and the present

05:42.884 --> 05:45.045
in terms of color.

05:46.346 --> 05:51.340
Every scene contains a hidden
or possible cliché,

05:51.434 --> 05:53.846
and we have to determine
what that cliché is

05:53.937 --> 05:57.771
so we can avoid it as much as possible.

05:57.858 --> 06:00.645
The cliché in a movie
set in both the present and the past

06:00.735 --> 06:03.977
is that everything in the present
is colorful and alive,

06:04.072 --> 06:06.279
while the past is black and white or sepia.

06:06.366 --> 06:08.982
We wanted to do exactly the opposite,

06:09.786 --> 06:13.904
not only to avoid doing what everyone does,

06:13.999 --> 06:16.240
what we've seen so many times,

06:16.334 --> 06:19.167
but also because,
since this is a movie about memory,

06:20.380 --> 06:22.917
the past has color, too.

06:23.008 --> 06:26.876
We don't remember the past
in black and white, but rather in color.

06:26.970 --> 06:32.090
But the dominant colors
in the scenes we remember are simpler.

06:32.183 --> 06:35.175
In the present everything is similar,

06:35.270 --> 06:39.764
everything is somewhat faded, even.

06:39.858 --> 06:44.022
We're all watching the same scene,
yet if we had to close our eyes

06:44.112 --> 06:49.232
and describe the colors we see,
we wouldn't remember it.

06:49.326 --> 06:54.821
In memories, though,
we always assign a color to every object.

06:54.915 --> 06:59.500
Here in the present, we work with colors

06:59.586 --> 07:03.625
that are quite muted and diluted,

07:03.715 --> 07:06.377
with a softer palette.

07:06.468 --> 07:09.301
The only exception is the reds

07:09.387 --> 07:13.130
that abound in Irene's world.

07:13.224 --> 07:18.469
It's in her clothing,
in the flower and in the curtains.

07:18.563 --> 07:19.928
The color red is a link,

07:20.023 --> 07:25.438
the only link between the Irene
of the present and the Irene of the past.

07:25.528 --> 07:30.568
This is true from both a thematic
perspective and a color perspective.

07:30.659 --> 07:36.746
We'll see Irene's penchant for reds
in the past as well.

07:39.793 --> 07:41.124
I don't know why.

07:41.878 --> 07:43.163
It's been on my mind.

07:43.463 --> 07:47.706
Our first little visual effect
of the movie is here.

07:47.801 --> 07:54.013
The logo of the café
that brought us coffee that day

07:54.099 --> 07:56.886
was on those cups.

07:56.977 --> 07:58.968
We had to erase them on the computer.

08:01.398 --> 08:05.391
That's just a taste of
all the visual effects

08:05.485 --> 08:08.397
in the movie that are coming up soon.

08:08.488 --> 08:12.982
There are 109 takes with effects in the
movie, not including the stadium scene.

08:13.827 --> 08:14.987
Here, let me.

08:15.453 --> 08:17.660
I can't...

08:20.250 --> 08:21.535
It weighs a ton.

08:22.085 --> 08:26.795
There is a strong chemistry
between soledad villamil and Ricardo Darin.

08:26.881 --> 08:29.418
We discovered this
in same love, same rain,

08:29.509 --> 08:32.626
and it's apparent to anyone
who has seen that movie.

08:33.429 --> 08:37.298
Though these actors get along
just fine professionally,

08:37.392 --> 08:40.304
we've all worked together for many years,

08:40.395 --> 08:46.140
they're not lifelong friends
who hang out all the time or anything.

08:46.234 --> 08:50.898
As soon as we started working,
the friendship, the chemistry between them

08:50.989 --> 08:54.732
was obvious, like in this scene.

08:54.826 --> 08:58.114
It makes any dialogue
you could possibly write

08:58.204 --> 09:02.948
to demonstrate the love between them
banal and superfluous.

09:03.043 --> 09:07.878
It's glaringly obvious
in the way they look at each other.

09:07.964 --> 09:10.171
Miss Irene menendez Hastings.

09:10.425 --> 09:11.540
"Hastings."

09:11.634 --> 09:14.216
We can see here
that the skin tones are more prominent.

09:14.304 --> 09:18.217
The red she's wearing
is a link to the past.

09:18.308 --> 09:22.768
But we can also see
that the green tones are intensified,

09:22.854 --> 09:24.594
the red tones are intensified.

09:24.689 --> 09:29.979
The color of the wood in the courts
is almost fiery.

09:30.070 --> 09:32.402
This is where Guillermo francella comes in.

09:32.489 --> 09:37.358
For those of you watching
who aren't from Argentina,

09:37.452 --> 09:42.116
he's a huge star in our country.

09:42.207 --> 09:45.199
He's a very popular person
and a very famous actor

09:45.293 --> 09:49.707
best known for his comedic work.

09:49.798 --> 09:54.508
We decided to introduce him
to the audience gradually,

09:54.594 --> 09:59.588
so that his mere appearance
wouldn't provoke laughter or exclamations

09:59.682 --> 10:02.594
or shift the weight of the plot.

10:02.685 --> 10:06.098
We saw him out of focus in the last scene.

10:06.189 --> 10:11.354
Here, we see his hands, his profile,
his back, slightly out of focus.

10:11.444 --> 10:14.982
And soon we'll see him in his entirety.

10:15.073 --> 10:19.066
This allowed us to moderate all the,
"look, it's francella!"

10:19.160 --> 10:21.822
That might've been heard in the theater.

10:22.080 --> 10:23.365
Hi, fellas.

10:23.456 --> 10:24.456
Good morning.

10:24.582 --> 10:26.914
Ma'am, did a Saint die this morning?

10:27.001 --> 10:32.541
Shooting in 235:1, or wide-screen format,

10:33.216 --> 10:36.708
eliminates the need for establishing shots.

10:36.803 --> 10:41.547
In each shot,
the characters, the architecture,

10:41.641 --> 10:44.223
everything around us is important.

10:44.310 --> 10:48.053
That's a huge advantage of this format

10:48.148 --> 10:53.563
over a square television format

10:53.653 --> 10:55.985
or even the wide-screen format of hdtv,

10:56.072 --> 10:59.155
which, with an aspect ratio of 16:9,
is much wider than this one.

10:59.325 --> 11:02.362
Well, I may dress like a toad...

11:02.453 --> 11:07.664
It was easy to work with
Guillermo francella

11:07.750 --> 11:12.164
in the sense that he's a great actor
and things come easily to him.

11:12.255 --> 11:16.624
But the approach we took with him...
The word "energy" comes up again.

11:16.718 --> 11:21.929
This character's energy
tends to take him to his desk

11:22.015 --> 11:25.178
to hide behind all those stacks of files,

11:26.311 --> 11:31.851
to use the act of binding case records

11:32.192 --> 11:37.903
or going downstairs as a crutch,
and to use subtle, low-key irony,

11:37.989 --> 11:43.325
energetically low-key, that is,
instead of open farce.

11:43.995 --> 11:46.327
Ask judge fortuna.

11:47.540 --> 11:49.531
I want a solution,
not two problems.

11:49.626 --> 11:52.163
Why is asking me a problem?

11:53.504 --> 11:56.541
It's not that.
It just seemed silly...

11:56.633 --> 11:58.498
To bother you with...

11:58.593 --> 12:02.131
A small detail, the person typing
in the back was a mistake.

12:02.222 --> 12:06.465
The typewriter in front of him
that's blocking his hands

12:06.559 --> 12:08.675
was actually another computer effect.

12:08.770 --> 12:12.638
The man was typing at the desk,
but he didn't have a typewriter.

12:12.732 --> 12:14.222
No one noticed during filming.

12:16.402 --> 12:21.317
Here, the tone between these two characters
is deliberately humorous.

12:21.407 --> 12:22.988
The humor is very dry.

12:23.076 --> 12:27.160
They even tell jokes
as we go down the corridor.

12:27.247 --> 12:33.243
There's a point where inspector baez
makes a witty remark.

12:34.921 --> 12:37.879
Here. That made people
laugh in the theater.

12:37.966 --> 12:41.333
We're entering a world
you could almost call comedic.

12:41.427 --> 12:42.963
It's the comedy of work.

12:43.054 --> 12:47.172
Everything is emphasized
so that what comes next,

12:47.267 --> 12:51.476
the character's shock,
is experienced by the audience as well.

12:51.562 --> 12:54.645
We're not just showing it to them,
they feel it, too.

12:54.732 --> 12:56.643
So we arrive laughing...

13:08.454 --> 13:13.244
The tone changes radically,
not only for him, but also for us.

13:15.712 --> 13:19.830
Because we're experiencing it firsthand,
we can understand

13:21.467 --> 13:25.756
the shock the character experiences
when he sees

13:25.847 --> 13:29.806
that exposed, fragile, mutilated body.

13:33.855 --> 13:38.645
This moment triggers everything
that happens next and changes his life.

13:41.988 --> 13:43.728
This part was filmed with dialogue.

13:43.823 --> 13:48.613
You could hear the inspector's voice
and that of the coroner,

13:48.703 --> 13:52.116
brilliantly played by Ricardo cerone.

13:53.166 --> 13:55.248
There was almost black-humor dialogue here

14:00.840 --> 14:06.210
I decided to cut this dialogue in editing.

14:06.304 --> 14:10.764
I wanted everything to be out of focus

14:10.850 --> 14:16.686
and to concentrate solely on esposito
and the dead woman,

14:16.773 --> 14:19.389
on the connection between them.

14:25.531 --> 14:27.146
The old lady mentioned...

14:27.241 --> 14:29.778
Two builders working
on the terrace in number 3...

14:29.869 --> 14:34.784
We also had takes where you could see
gioia, baez, speaking in focus,

14:35.208 --> 14:37.790
but I decided to go this route.

14:39.087 --> 14:41.874
- See you later, esposito.
- I'll go with you.

14:55.728 --> 14:59.346
Morales' character, the widower,
comes in here.

14:59.440 --> 15:01.601
Of all the characters,

15:01.692 --> 15:07.107
we had the hardest time deciding
how his reactions should be.

15:07.198 --> 15:11.282
There are obviously two sides
to his personality,

15:11.369 --> 15:15.738
two conflicting
and apparently very antagonistic sides.

15:15.832 --> 15:19.745
On the one hand, there's
the passionate love

15:21.754 --> 15:24.336
that will make him imprison himself
his whole life.

15:24.424 --> 15:28.337
His life ends right here
because of that passionate love.

15:28.428 --> 15:31.511
On the other hand,
there's the cold, methodical personality

15:31.597 --> 15:36.387
that leads him to formulate
a very difficult plan

15:36.477 --> 15:41.767
and maintain a silence and lifestyle
for 25 years without giving himself away.

15:42.859 --> 15:47.398
We opted for this approach,
which Pablo rago is doing here,

15:47.488 --> 15:49.194
and which he does extremely well.

15:49.282 --> 15:53.776
Instead of a person
who breaks down crying and screaming,

15:53.870 --> 15:57.658
which might be more normal, more real,

15:57.748 --> 16:00.785
we see a person
who is breaking apart inside,

16:00.877 --> 16:05.371
a person whose pain
is accompanied by a sort of coldness,

16:05.465 --> 16:07.797
a person whose eyes are making a decision.

16:11.053 --> 16:16.844
Right now, his eyes are saying,
"I'm going to catch that man."

16:23.941 --> 16:25.556
We transition with memories here.

16:25.651 --> 16:29.735
We thought that it was
the details people remember,

16:29.822 --> 16:32.734
like a kettle whistling.

16:32.825 --> 16:35.111
And from esposito's perspective, perhaps,

16:35.203 --> 16:39.446
all he saw in that scene was morales' back
and the steam from the kettle.

16:40.291 --> 16:43.328
- Who will want it?
- Just get it out of my sight.

16:44.337 --> 16:51.175
Here we start setting up the running gag,
the typewriter.

16:51.260 --> 16:53.501
I, criminal judge
raimundo fortuna lacalle...

16:53.596 --> 16:54.927
Hereby declare myself...

16:55.014 --> 16:59.428
This composition, which 235:1 allows,
is wonderful.

16:59.519 --> 17:01.475
Playing with different shots.

17:03.689 --> 17:08.979
The connection between them starts here.

17:10.029 --> 17:15.615
We start to see other facets
of Irene's highly efficient character.

17:15.701 --> 17:18.943
She can pick up on an office joke.

17:19.038 --> 17:21.119
Legally-speaking, insane...

17:21.207 --> 17:25.290
You'll see this type of framing
from below a lot in the movie,

17:25.377 --> 17:29.371
with many elements in the foreground
blocking our view.

17:33.844 --> 17:39.555
The purpose of all this was to make us,
as viewers, feel like we were hiding

17:39.642 --> 17:44.477
in a corner of this office,
trying to see what was going on.

17:44.564 --> 17:49.058
This adds the element
of spying on the story,

17:49.151 --> 17:52.314
of looking over the characters' shoulders.

17:52.405 --> 17:56.990
As a result, we get even more involved

17:57.076 --> 17:59.658
because we're trying to find out
what's going on.

17:59.745 --> 18:03.784
Benjamin, just to show you court 18
is acting in good faith...

18:03.958 --> 18:07.200
Remember you were upset the other day
over getting a case?

18:08.546 --> 18:10.377
Well, the case has been solved.

18:11.507 --> 18:14.249
Two builders working in number 3.

18:14.594 --> 18:16.334
They're under arrest in the 25th.

18:16.804 --> 18:18.590
Whenever you have a chance...

18:18.681 --> 18:22.674
In this scene, we start to see
two of the great discoveries in the movie.

18:22.768 --> 18:26.852
Mariano argento, playing Romano,

18:26.939 --> 18:32.775
and Mario alarcon,
playing judge fortuna lacalle.

18:33.779 --> 18:37.522
He won all the courts' unofficial awards

18:37.617 --> 18:41.656
as the most real and believable character
in the movie

18:41.746 --> 18:44.078
according to people who work in the courts.

18:46.000 --> 18:47.490
Esposito, how are you?

18:48.002 --> 18:51.119
Here we have a different color palette,
the color of memory.

18:51.213 --> 18:54.626
Everything is forced,
everything takes on a greenish hue

18:54.717 --> 18:57.800
when we look outside,
that fluorescent light.

18:57.887 --> 19:02.927
And here, as we walk in,
everything takes on a reddish hue.

19:04.143 --> 19:06.680
A strong red. We transition from daylight,

19:06.771 --> 19:10.764
which is colder and clearer,
to the light of a catacomb.

19:10.858 --> 19:12.519
A dangling light bulb.

19:12.610 --> 19:15.522
Here we see that transition occur faster.

19:15.613 --> 19:20.073
Outside the cell,
the cold fluorescent light we see there,

19:20.159 --> 19:23.572
and inside, a deep red

19:23.663 --> 19:27.155
illuminated by an incandescent bulb.

19:28.042 --> 19:29.452
He's caceres.

19:38.302 --> 19:39.462
Caceres.

19:43.182 --> 19:44.388
It's okay.

19:54.151 --> 19:57.439
You see that mixture
of cold light and warm light a lot

19:57.530 --> 20:00.943
in the corridors of the courts,
like in this scene.

20:01.033 --> 20:05.276
The courts are designed
with this huge skylight in the middle,

20:05.371 --> 20:09.535
in the hollow you see outside the
corridors, which we'll see now.

20:09.625 --> 20:12.458
It provides a lot of white daylight,

20:12.545 --> 20:15.457
but that light falls
right in the middle of the corridor,

20:15.548 --> 20:22.044
to such an extent that the offices require
artificial lighting.

20:22.138 --> 20:26.472
As a result, there's that constant mixture
of hot and cold in the courts,

20:26.559 --> 20:30.973
of cold light in the middle of the
corridor, which we enhance and make green,

20:31.063 --> 20:35.557
and the artificial light in the offices,
which we make red.

20:35.651 --> 20:37.437
There's a constant mix.

20:37.528 --> 20:39.860
We can even see it in
the characters' faces,

20:39.947 --> 20:43.986
almost green here and almost red there.

20:44.076 --> 20:47.068
It's a very distinct mix
that's quite noticeable in the courts

20:47.163 --> 20:51.122
and it gives us this atmosphere
of simultaneous interiors and exteriors.

20:51.208 --> 20:54.871
It allows us to create an atmosphere
of simultaneous day and night.

20:54.962 --> 20:56.873
It's a very interesting mix.

20:59.341 --> 21:00.831
Now we go to the dive bar.

21:00.926 --> 21:05.340
The dive bar was filmed
right on paseo colén,

21:05.431 --> 21:07.763
which is where it would actually be.

21:07.850 --> 21:11.058
We had to install double-pane glass
in all the windows

21:11.145 --> 21:15.935
so we could film the scene
and so the street noise

21:17.276 --> 21:19.642
wouldn't interfere with
the sound recording.

21:19.737 --> 21:24.276
And everything you see out the windows
was done by computer, too.

21:24.366 --> 21:27.199
We didn't have control over the street,

21:27.286 --> 21:30.619
so the cars that would be driving by
would be modern cars, of course.

21:30.706 --> 21:34.699
We had to put green screens
in all the windows

21:34.794 --> 21:38.628
and make the set later by computer

21:38.714 --> 21:41.205
with the cars we wanted to insert.

21:41.300 --> 21:44.633
The cars that drive by are just photos
of cars driving by,

21:44.720 --> 21:48.429
they're not 3D cars or anything.

21:51.060 --> 21:52.800
Sandoval's drunkenness...

