in a showball effect in real time,
because there are no cuts.

42:32.508 --> 42:35.250
This wouldn't have been the case

42:35.344 --> 42:38.632
if, for example,
we had cut to Ricardo's reaction

42:38.723 --> 42:40.554
to see what was going on.

42:40.641 --> 42:44.759
This works well
because we didn't stop in any one shot.

42:45.396 --> 42:47.682
A black peugeot was parked...

42:47.774 --> 42:53.110
With a Buenos Aires license plate
number 133-809...

42:53.196 --> 42:54.982
And my colleague asks
the federal police...

42:55.073 --> 42:58.236
The presence of Guillermo's character,
out of focus,

42:58.326 --> 43:01.068
but in a strategic part
of the screen aims to...

43:01.537 --> 43:06.702
He's the edge of a triangle.
The judge and esposito are the base

43:06.793 --> 43:12.129
and sandoval is at the other apex,
drawing our gaze.

43:12.215 --> 43:16.128
We're listening to the judge, but watching
sandoval, even though he's out of focus.

43:24.894 --> 43:25.974
Fo?

43:28.439 --> 43:31.272
Sandoval is the audience right now.

43:31.359 --> 43:36.570
He's holding back laughter.
We can laugh, but he's holding it back.

43:36.656 --> 43:38.772
This was planned, of course.

43:39.117 --> 43:43.360
To see if I can clear things up.
And the truth is, esposito, I can't.

43:43.454 --> 43:45.820
Because I don't look like
a judge anymore...

43:45.915 --> 43:48.452
I look like a first class
fucking idiot.

43:48.543 --> 43:53.333
Because I say I want a
and people give me z.

43:53.422 --> 43:56.539
I can't even watch this scene
without laughing.

43:59.971 --> 44:01.552
Excuse me, sir, but...

44:03.432 --> 44:05.138
I think something weird
is going on here.

44:05.226 --> 44:06.557
Again, we see...

44:07.812 --> 44:12.226
In a world where all the characters

44:12.316 --> 44:16.355
wear gray, black and brown,

44:16.445 --> 44:20.609
all colors from a very muted,
monochromatic palette,

44:20.700 --> 44:26.070
Irene, by contrast,
is always a source of color.

44:26.164 --> 44:27.404
Or that one of them was seen...

44:27.498 --> 44:31.992
Tying his shoelaces
when he was wearing loafers.

44:32.670 --> 44:37.289
What stood out most was that one of them
walked into the grocery store...

44:37.383 --> 44:39.499
Greeted them pleasantly...

44:39.594 --> 44:44.714
Asked for a bottle of whiskey and left
drinking straight from the bottle.

44:45.600 --> 44:47.841
Shall I describe him for you?

44:48.519 --> 44:50.350
We have to deny it, Benjamin.

44:50.438 --> 44:53.225
"It wasn't me, I don't know..."

44:53.316 --> 44:56.274
Don't ever talk to me again.
Never again.

44:56.360 --> 45:01.195
It may not look like it, but a lot
of special effects went into this scene.

45:01.282 --> 45:03.819
These days,
all the paint in the courts is peeling.

45:03.910 --> 45:06.868
The paint on those columns
in the background is peeling.

45:06.954 --> 45:08.785
It wasn't like that in the '70s.

45:08.873 --> 45:14.163
Trying to fix all that on the computer
created a domino effect of special effects.

45:14.253 --> 45:17.165
For example, we had to reproduce
the breath vapor

45:17.256 --> 45:19.747
that comes out of esposito"s mouth,

45:19.842 --> 45:24.586
because when we erased the original color
of the columns, the vapor got erased, too.

45:27.058 --> 45:28.923
That sort of thing.

45:29.018 --> 45:34.183
We had to erase a fire extinguisher
on a wall,

45:34.273 --> 45:38.642
but then we had to reproduce shadows.

45:38.736 --> 45:43.776
It's not that easy.
You say, "okay, let's erase it,"

45:43.866 --> 45:47.984
but sometimes you forget
that everything in front of that object

45:48.079 --> 45:51.663
also gets erased
and then has to be reproduced.

45:51.749 --> 45:55.708
Only one reference to a woman,
Rosa, apparently an aunt.

45:57.380 --> 46:00.087
That's it. That's all I've got.
The rest is nothing.

46:00.174 --> 46:02.381
- Benjamin.
- This is nothing too?

46:02.468 --> 46:04.254
Please.

46:15.481 --> 46:16.891
Leave it open, it isn't private.

46:18.609 --> 46:20.349
I talked to fortuna.

46:20.444 --> 46:22.685
I explained that you're an imbecile.

46:22.780 --> 46:23.799
I used my irresistible smile...

46:23.823 --> 46:26.781
The use of frame composition again.

46:26.867 --> 46:32.578
The person in control is well-placed,
on the left side of the frame...

46:32.665 --> 46:37.034
It's Irene, with all the space
to the right, where it should be.

46:38.170 --> 46:41.207
And the person who is not in control
is on the right side of the frame,

46:41.299 --> 46:43.039
in the larger plane, of course.

46:45.553 --> 46:48.090
Of course not.
I save it for my boyfriend, as I should.

46:48.180 --> 46:51.297
There's the red element
in Irene's clothing.

46:52.059 --> 46:53.139
Right.

46:54.312 --> 46:56.394
I won't take any more of your time.

46:56.480 --> 47:00.268
And bring me the Liliana coloto file,
to seal it and archive it.

47:05.865 --> 47:07.480
The case is closed.

47:16.834 --> 47:20.167
Getting engaged.
Kids today laugh at it.

47:20.254 --> 47:22.085
Who gets engaged anymore?

47:22.840 --> 47:24.501
We return to the present

47:26.427 --> 47:28.213
and to pale colors,

47:29.555 --> 47:32.718
except for Irene's red element.

47:34.852 --> 47:38.640
This is a good time to point out
Alex mathews' make-up.

47:38.731 --> 47:42.098
We can all see it

47:42.193 --> 47:45.310
in Ricardo's face,

47:45.404 --> 47:50.068
those perfect wrinkles that stand up
to the most extreme close-up,

47:50.159 --> 47:55.699
but also the subtlety of the makeup
on Irene's neck.

47:55.790 --> 48:00.329
Those tiny little wrinkles on her neck.

48:01.045 --> 48:04.537
The subtlest thing

48:04.632 --> 48:07.499
around her eyes is really remarkable.

48:07.593 --> 48:13.304
This is complemented
by soledad villamil's acting, of course.

48:13.391 --> 48:17.350
Her whole attitude changes
from the past to the present.

48:17.436 --> 48:21.770
In the past, she's a girl,
a scared rookie in a man's world

48:21.857 --> 48:23.973
who doesn't know how to assert herself,

48:24.068 --> 48:28.562
and who may not have a strong sense
of self-awareness.

48:28.656 --> 48:32.990
In the present, she's a
judge in her element

48:33.077 --> 48:36.285
who is used to controlling her territory.

48:37.123 --> 48:38.659
I was another person.

48:53.347 --> 48:55.258
Your novel might be really good.

48:56.517 --> 48:57.927
But it's not for me.

49:00.604 --> 49:04.973
You've reached the end of your life
and you want to look back.

49:05.985 --> 49:07.316
But I can't.

49:08.279 --> 49:10.986
I have to go to work every day.

49:12.450 --> 49:15.658
And live with this.
It may not be true justice...

49:15.744 --> 49:17.655
But it's a kind of justice.

49:19.790 --> 49:22.281
And at the end of the day
I have to go home...

49:23.085 --> 49:24.621
And live with my husband...

49:25.754 --> 49:27.710
And with my children,
who I adore.

49:30.676 --> 49:33.042
My whole life I've looked forward.

49:35.639 --> 49:38.176
The past is out of my jurisdiction.

49:38.309 --> 49:40.140
I declare myself incompetent.

49:48.944 --> 49:50.684
What a case, Jesus Christ.

49:52.156 --> 49:53.862
It never dies.

50:09.340 --> 50:12.298
We filmed this scene in retiro station
in half an hour

50:12.384 --> 50:14.420
because they were
practically kicking us out.

50:14.512 --> 50:17.720
It was a Saturday afternoon,
almost nighttime,

50:17.806 --> 50:20.218
and the station was starting to fill up.

50:22.061 --> 50:24.302
This is one of my favorite scenes.

50:27.024 --> 50:29.515
Pablo rago does an exceptional job here.

50:29.610 --> 50:33.398
I think we get the feeling that he's a man
on the verge of madness,

50:33.489 --> 50:35.775
but isn't quite there yet.

50:37.493 --> 50:43.705
For me, this is the most disturbing scene
for this character.

50:44.542 --> 50:45.907
Yes.

50:51.048 --> 50:52.333
How are things?

50:52.883 --> 50:54.194
This month I'm here Tuesdays and...

50:54.218 --> 50:56.755
Once again, we see those frames
where the layout

50:56.845 --> 51:00.884
and architecture of the place dominate.

51:02.893 --> 51:07.557
It's a story about two small men
in a huge place, teeming with people.

51:08.566 --> 51:13.981
This was one of the images
I began the treatment of the movie with.

51:14.071 --> 51:15.481
Looking at retiro station,

51:15.573 --> 51:20.067
noticing that all these scenes are set
in huge places.

51:20.160 --> 51:23.823
We see retiro station, a huge place

51:23.914 --> 51:28.123
with 1,000 or 500 people walking around.

51:28.210 --> 51:29.370
A swarm of people.

51:29.461 --> 51:34.501
What would happen if we could suddenly
cut to a close-up of the eyes

51:34.592 --> 51:36.332
of one of those people?

51:36.427 --> 51:39.169
What story would their eyes tell us?

51:39.263 --> 51:43.757
That was the premise
for the treatment of the movie.

51:44.893 --> 51:48.932
That combination of huge places
and close-ups of eyes.

51:51.984 --> 51:55.568
I think Pablo's expression here adds depth.

51:55.654 --> 51:57.940
We don't know if he's crazy,

51:59.617 --> 52:03.280
if he's serious, if he's human,
if he's a man in love...

52:06.707 --> 52:08.243
Then I start having doubts...

52:09.084 --> 52:12.201
And I don't remember if it was lemon
or honey in the tea.

52:14.131 --> 52:16.484
And I don't know if it's a memory
or a memory of a memory...

52:16.508 --> 52:20.000
Until this point,
when we're moved by his pain.

52:32.483 --> 52:33.483
Excuse me.

52:34.109 --> 52:36.475
This is one of my favorite scenes
in the movie.

52:36.570 --> 52:40.154
I'm going to say something quickly
and let you watch it.

52:40.240 --> 52:43.232
In this scene, the idea that
a person's eyes tell one story

52:43.327 --> 52:46.410
while his words tell another is crucial.

52:46.497 --> 52:52.242
Also, all the storylines are addressed
at the same time.

52:52.336 --> 52:56.079
The story of the crime progresses,

52:56.173 --> 52:58.414
the love story progresses,

52:58.509 --> 53:01.000
the story of Pablo rago progresses.

53:03.180 --> 53:05.592
It functions
on all those levels simultaneously.

53:05.683 --> 53:10.143
Thematically, it's a scene
in which all the storylines converge.

53:10.396 --> 53:13.012
Go on. Yes.

53:14.525 --> 53:15.856
And I thought...

53:16.610 --> 53:18.225
"I have to talk to Irene."

53:19.113 --> 53:22.651
In terms of tone, there's romance,

53:23.534 --> 53:26.025
suspense and comedy.

53:27.079 --> 53:29.724
It's another thing that really
fascinated me while making this movie.

53:29.748 --> 53:32.660
To what point can we combine those flavors,

53:33.752 --> 53:38.712
those types of music, those rhythms
and those energies

53:38.799 --> 53:42.883
and still have
a cohesive and effective product?

53:43.387 --> 53:44.877
Excuse me, ma'am.

53:55.441 --> 53:57.477
I ran into morales yesterday
at the train station.

53:59.236 --> 54:00.567
Know what he was doing?

54:01.405 --> 54:02.986
My crystal ball is broken.

54:05.743 --> 54:09.577
He goes to the terminals every day
looking for the killer.

54:09.663 --> 54:12.780
Every single day after working
at the bank.

54:13.417 --> 54:16.659
There's also a small
detail here of the Rose,

54:16.754 --> 54:20.588
which looks like it's on esposito's lapel.

54:21.008 --> 54:24.751
It's as if his wife's death
just left him there...

54:24.928 --> 54:26.964
Stuck in time forever.

54:28.891 --> 54:30.927
You should see his eyes.

54:32.936 --> 54:35.177
They're in a state of pure love.

54:36.690 --> 54:38.726
Can you imagine a love like that?

54:38.817 --> 54:42.435
Unaffected by the wear and tear
of the routine?

54:45.949 --> 54:47.689
Speak for yourself,
I don't know about that.

54:52.831 --> 54:54.867
We think the guy...

54:54.958 --> 54:57.415
Deserves another chance, ma'am.

55:00.255 --> 55:01.335
Where do I come in?

55:01.757 --> 55:02.872
The case is closed.

55:02.966 --> 55:04.331
We'd have to reopen it.

55:06.637 --> 55:09.094
You're asking me to destroy
an official document...

55:09.181 --> 55:11.797
With mine and the judge's
signature on it...

55:12.309 --> 55:14.721
And to falsify statements and dates...

55:14.812 --> 55:17.724
So it will look like the case
is still open?

55:17.815 --> 55:21.182
- That's a brilliant idea. We hadn't...
- Don't fuck with me.

55:42.589 --> 55:45.422
I think that the scene we just saw

55:45.509 --> 55:51.004
makes a very strong case
for working with actors.

55:53.809 --> 55:55.049
Tell me.

55:55.269 --> 55:58.102
Did you see a stack of letters
on my desk?

55:58.188 --> 55:59.268
No.

56:01.108 --> 56:02.188
Sandoval?

56:02.442 --> 56:03.648
He left down talcahuano.

56:03.735 --> 56:05.396
The case is reopened.

56:13.203 --> 56:16.161
Not only do you sneak off to get drunk,
you also steal evidence.

56:16.248 --> 56:18.079
Everything's under control.

56:18.166 --> 56:20.077
Here comes the scene about passion.

56:20.168 --> 56:21.283
Hands off. Are you nuts?

56:21.378 --> 56:22.458
We're going back.

56:22.546 --> 56:28.963
This is actually another system
commonly used by police and detectives

56:29.052 --> 56:32.636
for finding missing people.

56:32.723 --> 56:38.263
Learning what that person loves most,
what his vices and passions are,

56:38.353 --> 56:40.969
because those things are
very hard to change.

56:41.064 --> 56:44.147
For example,
if a person is addicted to gambling,

56:44.234 --> 56:48.853
he can drop off the radar,
but he'll take that addiction with him.

56:48.947 --> 56:53.907
The same thing happens here,
and we draw a sort of metaphor

56:53.994 --> 56:58.078
for the main theme of the movie, passions.

56:58.916 --> 57:00.281
The passions that control us.

57:00.375 --> 57:03.082
And I started thinking about guys.

57:03.837 --> 57:09.002
Guys in general.
Not just this guy, but...

57:09.092 --> 57:11.253
Guys in general.

57:11.845 --> 57:13.631
A guy.

57:15.432 --> 57:18.094
A guy can do anything
to be different.

57:18.852 --> 57:23.095
But there's one thing he can't change.
Not him, not you, not anybody.

57:24.608 --> 57:25.768
Take me, for example.

57:25.859 --> 57:28.441
Great acting by Guillermo francella...

57:29.112 --> 57:31.398
I have a good job,
a wife who loves me...

57:32.282 --> 57:35.900
With Ricardo's reactions,

57:35.994 --> 57:39.828
which are a perfect and subtle emphasis.

57:39.915 --> 57:41.496
"Why are you here, Pablo?"

57:42.751 --> 57:43.751
You know why, Benjamin?

57:43.877 --> 57:46.289
The rhythm of the scene is slow.

57:46.380 --> 57:51.670
The cadenza of this scene is piano,

57:51.760 --> 57:53.967
to put it in musical terms. Pianissimo.

57:55.472 --> 57:56.837
Two scenes later...

57:56.932 --> 58:02.802
I'm saying this because I'll explain why
we filmed the stadium scene the way we did.

58:03.355 --> 58:07.314
Two scenes later,
we're in an interrogation scene

58:07.401 --> 58:10.814
that lasts about 10 minutes.

58:11.780 --> 58:14.988
It's an intimate scene
with just three people,

58:15.075 --> 58:19.409
very little happens,
and it's set in an enclosed space.

58:19.496 --> 58:21.236
This scene is the same way.

58:21.331 --> 58:27.577
The energy curve of the movie
is going down, down,

58:27.671 --> 58:34.167
and we had to fulfill several functions
with the stadium scene.

58:35.137 --> 58:38.379
They had to find the man, of course.

58:38.473 --> 58:42.933
That's the narrative function,
its function in the script.

58:43.020 --> 58:48.811
But as viewers, we should also feel
a surge of energy at that moment.

58:48.900 --> 58:52.563
I needed to make viewers feel
what the characters feel,

58:52.654 --> 58:55.441
anguish and adrenaline.

58:55.532 --> 58:57.864
In a short span of time...

58:59.911 --> 59:01.697
Like a sandwich,

59:01.788 --> 59:05.280
between two low-energy scenes.

59:07.711 --> 59:09.576
So how do we do that?

59:09.671 --> 59:15.211
We'll see how this scene ends...
We'll resume when the stadium scene starts.

59:15.927 --> 59:18.213
"As anido with mesias."

59:18.305 --> 59:21.547
Anido and mesias, backs on the club
that won it all in '61.

59:21.641 --> 59:23.381
Negri at goalie, anido and mesias.

59:23.518 --> 59:26.555
Blanco, peano and sacchi.
Corbatta, pizzuti...

59:27.022 --> 59:29.013
Mansilla, sosa and Belen.

59:29.274 --> 59:32.812
"Don't worry about me.
I'm like manfredini...

59:32.903 --> 59:35.315
Not bavastro." Notary?

59:35.405 --> 59:37.191
Pedro waldemar manfredini.

59:37.282 --> 59:41.275
Racing paid peanuts for him
and he ended up being...

59:41.369 --> 59:45.533
An extraordinary player.
Incredible.

59:45.624 --> 59:47.990
Julio bavastro, right forward.

59:48.085 --> 59:52.169
Played only two matches
between '62 and '63 without scoring.

59:52.255 --> 59:54.371
Quote: "Il don't want
to end up like Sanchez."

59:54.466 --> 59:56.457
Who's he talking about?

59:56.551 --> 01:00:00.965
He can only mean the goalie,
ataulfo Sanchez.

01:00:01.056 --> 01:00:02.967
Eternal benchwarmer.

01:00:03.058 --> 01:00:07.848
He played only 17 matches
between '57 and '61.

01:00:07.938 --> 01:00:10.429
Notary, what is racing to you?

01:00:10.524 --> 01:00:11.889
A passion.

01:00:11.983 --> 01:00:13.848
Even after nine years
without a championship?

01:00:13.944 --> 01:00:16.185
A passion is a passion.

01:00:16.279 --> 01:00:17.644
You see, Benjamin?

01:00:17.739 --> 01:00:23.325
A guy can change anything.
His face, his home, his family...

01:00:23.411 --> 01:00:27.575
His girlfriend, his religion, his god.

01:00:27.666 --> 01:00:30.783
But there's one thing he can't change.

01:00:30.877 --> 01:00:31.912
He can't change...

01:00:32.003 --> 01:00:33.288
His passion.

01:00:34.506 --> 01:00:36.087
And here we are.

01:00:36.174 --> 01:00:38.665
A movie's energy curve is made up of

01:00:38.760 --> 01:00:41.593
moments of Harmony
and moments of change.

01:00:41.680 --> 01:00:43.045
Moments of Harmony,

01:00:43.140 --> 01:00:46.724
when we maintain
the same energy and style,

01:00:46.810 --> 01:00:49.802
make us feel at ease.

01:00:49.896 --> 01:00:53.639
They make us feel comfortable,
like we can follow the story.

01:00:53.733 --> 01:00:56.566
But moments of change
are the ones that excite us.

01:00:56.653 --> 01:01:00.362
They give us a surge of adrenaline
and pique our interest.

01:01:00.448 --> 01:01:05.363
Too much Harmony in a movie is boring.
Too much change is incoherent.

01:01:05.453 --> 01:01:11.039
We were coming off two intimate scenes
and we needed a surge of energy.

01:01:11.126 --> 01:01:16.211
We start with the cliché establishing shot
of the stadium, which was deliberate.

01:01:16.298 --> 01:01:20.382
Usually, viewers are
used to going to a cut.

01:01:20.468 --> 01:01:23.676
And here, we keep going and going
and going

01:01:23.763 --> 01:01:26.425
and going and going

01:01:26.516 --> 01:01:29.724
and going and we don't stop.

01:01:29.811 --> 01:01:32.598
The camera pauses at Ricardo
and keeps going.

01:01:32.689 --> 01:01:36.307
Those 30 seconds

01:01:36.401 --> 01:01:40.440
make us, the viewers,
feel like we we're sitting right there.

01:01:40.530 --> 01:01:44.443
We're in another world,
seeing something else, immersed,

01:01:44.534 --> 01:01:47.116
just another fan in the crowd.

01:01:47.204 --> 01:01:49.911
We never would've been
able to achieve this with a cut.

01:01:49.998 --> 01:01:51.989
It isn't a whim.

01:01:52.083 --> 01:01:57.498
It's the way to achieve, to its fullest,

01:01:57.589 --> 01:02:03.129
a sense of involvement in the scene,
the surge of energy we feel.

01:02:03.220 --> 01:02:07.930
If we had cut to this, if we had...

01:02:08.016 --> 01:02:09.381
Here, for example,

01:02:09.476 --> 01:02:12.809
we're a guy standing next to them
as francella says, "there he is!"

01:02:12.896 --> 01:02:17.640
We turn our head
and start walking behind them.

01:02:17.734 --> 01:02:20.316
And the whole time we're just
another person in the stadium.

01:02:20.403 --> 01:02:22.735
People even bump into us.

01:02:23.740 --> 01:02:24.900
Here.

01:02:25.909 --> 01:02:27.445
We're just another person.

01:02:28.411 --> 01:02:32.996
We were able to do all that
because we went from the aerial shot

01:02:33.083 --> 01:02:35.290
to the stands without a cut.

01:02:35.377 --> 01:02:37.584
And here again,

01:02:39.256 --> 01:02:43.295
every time we expect a cut,
it keeps going and going.

