01:21:47.736 --> 01:21:50.068
Come alone and we'll settle it.

01:21:55.577 --> 01:21:56.817
Come on, Irene.

01:21:56.912 --> 01:21:58.072
There are

01:22:00.249 --> 01:22:04.583
ample sources to support this version.

01:22:06.422 --> 01:22:08.083
Neither of you
can do a thing about it.

01:22:22.187 --> 01:22:25.099
And the descent into hell continues.

01:22:25.190 --> 01:22:29.103
The humiliation appears complete,
but we still have a long way to go.

01:22:46.962 --> 01:22:49.749
This is another scene that,

01:22:51.091 --> 01:22:56.211
had we done it with cuts,
would've lost all its power.

01:22:57.806 --> 01:22:59.637
Or at least some of its power.

01:23:01.310 --> 01:23:05.053
The elevator sound
that José Luis Diaz found

01:23:06.648 --> 01:23:11.392
adds a sort of ghostly
element to the scene,

01:23:11.487 --> 01:23:15.400
making any other type
of musical effect unnecessary.

01:23:15.491 --> 01:23:19.655
In this case,
it doesn't get gloomier than reality.

01:23:33.675 --> 01:23:34.881
You said life.

01:23:36.637 --> 01:23:37.843
Yes...

01:23:38.013 --> 01:23:39.423
Morales tried.

01:23:39.515 --> 01:23:43.758
And he collaborated with the authorities
in everything he did,

01:23:43.852 --> 01:23:45.888
giving them all the information he had.

01:23:47.814 --> 01:23:49.350
In this scene,

01:23:52.027 --> 01:23:54.860
he decides that he's on his own.

01:23:57.533 --> 01:23:59.273
If I could, what for?

01:23:59.868 --> 01:24:02.610
What would I do?
What would four bullets get me?

01:24:03.455 --> 01:24:04.820
A lifetime in jail.

01:24:05.541 --> 01:24:09.329
Gomez goes free without ever serving
and I spend 50 years...

01:24:09.419 --> 01:24:12.707
Stuck in a cell, envying him.

01:24:14.341 --> 01:24:15.341
No.

01:24:16.885 --> 01:24:20.548
No, life in prison
would have been fair.

01:24:24.393 --> 01:24:27.385
I wish I could help,
but I honestly don't know how.

01:24:31.733 --> 01:24:33.018
Who knows?

01:24:34.194 --> 01:24:35.559
Some other time...

01:24:41.326 --> 01:24:42.441
Anyway.

01:24:43.287 --> 01:24:44.902
- I'll get it.
- No, please.

01:24:44.997 --> 01:24:46.453
It's just a coffee.

01:24:51.086 --> 01:24:53.623
I'm very grateful for everything
you've done for me.

01:24:54.464 --> 01:24:56.671
I wouldn't have made it this far
without you.

01:24:59.261 --> 01:25:00.592
I owe you one.

01:25:03.098 --> 01:25:05.384
Morales already knows his future here.

01:25:12.274 --> 01:25:17.610
I think the major dilemmas,
the major dramatic conflicts,

01:25:17.696 --> 01:25:23.111
can be boiled down to two things,
threats to dignity and threats to life.

01:25:23.201 --> 01:25:27.820
Esposito's dignity
has been destroyed, tarnished.

01:25:27.914 --> 01:25:31.372
He has been humiliated
in the eyes of the law,

01:25:31.460 --> 01:25:33.451
in the eyes of the woman he loves,

01:25:35.339 --> 01:25:36.795
and in his own eyes.

01:25:39.468 --> 01:25:41.925
But his life isn't in danger yet.

01:25:43.263 --> 01:25:44.298
No, you aren't.

01:25:44.389 --> 01:25:47.131
You'd have to be there, but you're here.

01:25:51.063 --> 01:25:52.303
Benjamin.

01:25:55.776 --> 01:25:56.856
Yes?

01:25:59.529 --> 01:26:01.815
How long before you talk to me again?

01:26:02.366 --> 01:26:03.981
I talk to you every day.

01:26:06.870 --> 01:26:08.485
I'm not untouchable.

01:26:09.665 --> 01:26:10.745
Or from another world.

01:26:10.832 --> 01:26:14.495
But the case,
although it ended badly, is over.

01:26:17.214 --> 01:26:18.875
And their lives go on.

01:26:18.965 --> 01:26:24.050
So we decided, dramatically,

01:26:25.222 --> 01:26:29.181
to pull a sort of sleight of hand

01:26:29.851 --> 01:26:33.890
and make viewers believe we were moving
in the direction of the love story,

01:26:35.982 --> 01:26:39.520
and even in the direction
of romantic comedy.

01:26:41.321 --> 01:26:44.063
Irene wants to meet up with him,

01:26:45.826 --> 01:26:47.407
and clearly

01:26:49.329 --> 01:26:52.366
makes a date.

01:26:52.457 --> 01:26:53.559
About my life, my fiance...

01:26:53.583 --> 01:26:55.949
My marriage and anything else
related to the case.

01:27:00.048 --> 01:27:01.959
We can meet for coffee after work.

01:27:02.843 --> 01:27:03.958
Time?

01:27:07.723 --> 01:27:09.213
8:30. Place?

01:27:09.349 --> 01:27:11.340
- The immortals.
- The Richmond.

01:27:11.601 --> 01:27:15.219
We're back to the energy curve,
the tonal curve.

01:27:15.313 --> 01:27:21.559
We're coming off a very dramatic moment
that caused a lot of anguish

01:27:21.695 --> 01:27:23.651
and we're stepping into the light.

01:27:23.739 --> 01:27:26.196
We'll play in a major scale again,

01:27:26.283 --> 01:27:28.695
to put it in musical terms.

01:27:30.579 --> 01:27:32.499
It seems like this is the
direction it'll go in.

01:27:32.539 --> 01:27:35.997
Even this minor conflict here which,

01:27:36.501 --> 01:27:39.163
in a slightly somber way,

01:27:39.254 --> 01:27:43.588
shows us the conflict at that time
between a fascist...

01:27:43.675 --> 01:27:46.087
We can deduce
what the notary's position is.

01:27:46.178 --> 01:27:48.760
We can deduce what sandoval's position is.

01:27:49.890 --> 01:27:54.179
But it brings us to a witty remark,
something almost funny.

01:27:54.311 --> 01:27:57.269
I repeat, we're going to
play in a major scale.

01:28:00.066 --> 01:28:02.899
Even more so in the next scene.

01:28:02.986 --> 01:28:06.854
Arrest the motherfuckers!
Show them some fucking justice!

01:28:07.449 --> 01:28:09.440
- Fuck you!
- My jacket! My jacket!

01:28:09.534 --> 01:28:10.694
You're wearing it.

01:28:16.082 --> 01:28:18.198
It was important to see the bar
from the front,

01:28:18.293 --> 01:28:23.083
because later we'll see morales
watching the building from there.

01:28:24.800 --> 01:28:27.257
And this scene borders on the ridiculous.

01:28:27.344 --> 01:28:32.338
I must admit, I've never laughed as hard
as I did when we rehearsed this scene.

01:28:32.432 --> 01:28:36.516
At times like that, you feel privileged

01:28:36.603 --> 01:28:39.936
to work with two such actors.

01:28:40.774 --> 01:28:42.480
She's never going to answer.

01:28:42.859 --> 01:28:43.894
Why?

01:28:43.985 --> 01:28:45.441
Because the phone doesn't work.

01:28:45.529 --> 01:28:47.190
What do you mean? Put that down.

01:28:48.031 --> 01:28:49.217
I told you a thousand times...

01:28:49.241 --> 01:28:51.573
The timing of sandoval's responses...

01:28:53.328 --> 01:28:54.864
And you didn't help me.

01:28:55.580 --> 01:28:57.161
That was six months ago.

01:28:58.124 --> 01:29:00.365
The phone hasn't worked for a year.

01:29:00.460 --> 01:29:04.373
The way he moves, deliberately, slowly...

01:29:04.589 --> 01:29:06.625
Put that down.
Stop touching stuff.

01:29:07.717 --> 01:29:09.048
If you ever...

01:29:09.135 --> 01:29:14.971
The timing in this scene
is practically anti-comedic.

01:29:15.058 --> 01:29:16.298
I wanted to sue them.

01:29:18.228 --> 01:29:19.343
Look at me.

01:29:19.980 --> 01:29:22.221
- You have a date?
- No, no.

01:29:22.649 --> 01:29:25.061
You have a date.
And I'm leaving.

01:29:25.151 --> 01:29:28.314
The last thing I need
is you calling me a party pooper.

01:29:29.406 --> 01:29:31.818
Too much furniture in here.

01:29:31.908 --> 01:29:34.775
- Sit here.
- I always run into shit.

01:29:34.870 --> 01:29:37.737
Have a seat until you feel better.

01:29:37.831 --> 01:29:39.662
Have a seat.

01:29:39.749 --> 01:29:45.494
In short, all this leads viewers to believe
that the story will go like this,

01:29:45.589 --> 01:29:51.004
"now he'll hook up with Irene, sandoval will
be around, they'll have an affair, etc."

01:29:51.177 --> 01:29:54.044
I'll try to convince your wife
not to kill you.

01:29:55.140 --> 01:29:56.550
Call her on the phone.

01:29:56.641 --> 01:30:01.135
This steers us toward Harmony,
as I said, between Harmony and change.

01:30:03.064 --> 01:30:05.430
Mine doesn't work, Benjamin.

01:30:05.525 --> 01:30:06.856
Use yours.

01:30:11.406 --> 01:30:15.069
Just stay here. Don't touch anything,
don't do anything.

01:30:15.535 --> 01:30:17.196
I'll be right back.

01:30:18.580 --> 01:30:20.411
Turn off the light. Yes.

01:30:22.542 --> 01:30:25.158
We'll catch that son of a bitch.

01:30:25.253 --> 01:30:27.335
We'll catch him.

01:30:31.092 --> 01:30:35.426
- We were working all day.
- Save it, some other time.

01:30:35.722 --> 01:30:39.761
Again, if we were describing
a musical composition,

01:30:39.851 --> 01:30:43.218
we'd be talking about
a modulatory bridge here

01:30:44.981 --> 01:30:49.145
because there will be
a sudden change in tone.

01:30:49.235 --> 01:30:52.193
Actually, not a sudden change in tone,

01:30:52.280 --> 01:30:55.192
but rather a powerful change in tone,

01:30:55.283 --> 01:30:58.525
an important change in scale.

01:30:58.620 --> 01:31:01.953
We're gradually moving
from one scale to the other.

01:31:08.296 --> 01:31:09.296
Pablo?

01:31:09.714 --> 01:31:11.875
- What is it?
- I don't know. Pablo?

01:31:11.967 --> 01:31:14.379
- Don't scare me.
- Wait there.

01:31:15.553 --> 01:31:16.633
Pablo...

01:31:20.392 --> 01:31:23.429
- No!
- What is it? What happened?

01:31:26.481 --> 01:31:29.314
I'd like to start talking about the music.

01:31:31.695 --> 01:31:35.153
The music we're hearing now
isn't bombastic,

01:31:35.240 --> 01:31:39.734
it isn't dramatic, but it is tragic.

01:31:39.828 --> 01:31:42.285
The music has a hint of requiem,

01:31:42.372 --> 01:31:45.284
but it's almost angelic.

01:31:45.375 --> 01:31:50.119
This music diminishes,
acting as a counterpoint

01:31:51.464 --> 01:31:53.625
to this scene's dramatic surge.

01:31:53.967 --> 01:31:57.175
- He's gonna go after you.
- No, my father knows who to talk to.

01:31:57.429 --> 01:32:02.514
That was a brief introduction
to the subject of music.

01:32:02.600 --> 01:32:05.888
We've reached the last scene
of the second act.

01:32:05.979 --> 01:32:10.598
His dignity is clearly destroyed,
his life threatened.

01:32:10.692 --> 01:32:14.526
Everything is a lot worse
than when it started,

01:32:14.612 --> 01:32:16.523
with no solution in sight.

01:32:19.534 --> 01:32:22.116
This was the hardest scene to do
in the entire movie.

01:32:22.203 --> 01:32:23.318
Finding the right tone.

01:32:23.413 --> 01:32:26.120
Although esposito is remembering this,

01:32:26.207 --> 01:32:30.200
and we could therefore
have been overly melodramatic,

01:32:30.295 --> 01:32:33.913
we needed this scene to work

01:32:34.007 --> 01:32:36.669
with our 21st century sensibility.

01:32:37.552 --> 01:32:42.216
We begin with lots of subliminal themes,

01:32:42.307 --> 01:32:48.018
for example, we can see that all the actors
are wearing colors,

01:32:48.104 --> 01:32:50.561
while these two
are wearing black and white.

01:32:50.648 --> 01:32:54.140
It has a subliminal hint of the '40s,

01:32:55.528 --> 01:33:00.739
two people wrapped up
in one of those old romantic movies

01:33:00.825 --> 01:33:03.737
in a more modern world.

01:33:09.501 --> 01:33:12.993
Both federico jusid and Emilio kauderer
can attest to the fact

01:33:13.088 --> 01:33:17.798
that we never worked so hard
to find the right tone for the music.

01:33:17.884 --> 01:33:22.093
In the first version,
we went with melodrama, of course.

01:33:22.180 --> 01:33:26.890
It was very similar
to Lara's theme from Dr. Zhivago

01:33:27.685 --> 01:33:32.099
and transformed the scene
into something very sappy.

01:33:32.190 --> 01:33:33.851
It didn't work.

01:33:35.276 --> 01:33:41.693
The editing also went along with the music,
and that didn't work either.

01:33:41.783 --> 01:33:45.367
We had a very hard time
finding the right balance in the editing

01:33:45.453 --> 01:33:48.035
and in the music as well.

01:33:48.123 --> 01:33:52.457
In subsequent versions of the music,
I think there were more than 15,

01:33:52.544 --> 01:33:55.661
we always brought it down,
always less and less.

01:33:55.755 --> 01:33:57.666
First we took out instruments.

01:33:57.757 --> 01:34:00.043
Then we took out crescendos.

01:34:01.219 --> 01:34:05.553
The shot we're seeing now was almost
removed from the movie altogether

01:34:05.640 --> 01:34:11.431
because it always seemed too dramatic,
too melodramatic.

01:34:11.521 --> 01:34:15.105
I loved it, and we finally
found a place for it.

01:34:15.191 --> 01:34:20.356
It took several revisions, several edits,

01:34:20.446 --> 01:34:23.563
before we found the right balance

01:34:23.658 --> 01:34:27.492
between realism, melodrama and romance.

01:34:31.332 --> 01:34:34.074
This isn't a formula, of course,

01:34:34.169 --> 01:34:38.583
and the way we found this balance

01:34:38.673 --> 01:34:43.713
was by simply trying different things.
Trial and error the entire time.

01:34:43.803 --> 01:34:47.421
That's how we did it.

01:34:47.515 --> 01:34:49.722
End of the second act. The curtain falls.

01:34:54.731 --> 01:34:56.562
"With you, the actors,"

01:34:57.275 --> 01:34:59.982
as they used to say in an old TV show.

01:35:07.243 --> 01:35:08.723
We're playing with memory here again.

01:35:08.786 --> 01:35:14.907
We'll never know if that train scene
happened the way we saw it

01:35:15.501 --> 01:35:19.961
or if esposito is
remembering it differently.

01:35:21.799 --> 01:35:23.414
Your house is exactly
as I imagined it.

01:35:23.509 --> 01:35:25.875
How did you imagine it?

01:35:26.512 --> 01:35:29.379
Exactly like this.
Exactly like I imagined it.

01:35:29.515 --> 01:35:30.675
Sure...

01:35:31.059 --> 01:35:34.722
We start with a major key again.

01:35:36.648 --> 01:35:40.232
When I say major key and minor key,
I'm referring to

01:35:42.528 --> 01:35:46.396
a musical explanation
of the energy in the movie.

01:35:46.491 --> 01:35:51.281
In a major key, all the notes seem to fall
where they're supposed to.

01:35:51.371 --> 01:35:52.907
In a minor key,

01:35:54.165 --> 01:35:59.330
there are always one or two notes
that fall in an odd place.

01:35:59.420 --> 01:36:04.335
They give us a strange feeling.
There's stress in the music.

01:36:06.886 --> 01:36:10.754
So here we start in a major key
and quickly move to a minor key.

01:36:11.432 --> 01:36:13.548
Or even believable.

01:36:13.643 --> 01:36:15.884
Yes. No. What?
It isn't believable?

01:36:16.896 --> 01:36:21.435
Irene's character uses a system of attack

01:36:22.443 --> 01:36:24.775
common to courtroom dramas...

01:36:24.862 --> 01:36:28.104
From a direction standpoint even...

01:36:29.117 --> 01:36:34.703
The lawyer who, using the socratic method,
with yes or no questions,

01:36:34.789 --> 01:36:38.202
leads the witness into a trap.

01:36:38.293 --> 01:36:42.878
She even moves toward him gradually
until he has no way out.

01:36:42.964 --> 01:36:45.125
Love she'd never had
the courage to confess...

01:36:45.258 --> 01:36:47.715
That's what happened. Isn't it?

01:36:52.098 --> 01:36:53.338
If that's what happened...

01:36:56.686 --> 01:36:58.051
Why didn't you take me with you?

01:36:58.396 --> 01:37:01.934
Again, we see Irene the judge,
Irene from the interrogation,

01:37:03.651 --> 01:37:05.357
in a romantic scene.

01:37:12.452 --> 01:37:13.567
Dimwit.

01:37:32.472 --> 01:37:34.884
How does the case proceed?

01:37:36.684 --> 01:37:41.053
There are no longer any secrets between
them, only the impossibility of closeness.

01:37:42.523 --> 01:37:45.606
The only thing left to tear down

01:37:45.693 --> 01:37:47.729
is that wall.

01:37:49.906 --> 01:37:55.117
Or that he came back married
to a rich little jujuyan Princess.

01:37:55.203 --> 01:37:56.864
She was wonderful.

01:37:57.538 --> 01:37:59.779
It wasn't her fault
I could never love her.

01:38:04.712 --> 01:38:06.828
It's a lousy ending.

01:38:06.923 --> 01:38:08.333
It's crap.

01:38:09.967 --> 01:38:11.252
You see?

01:38:11.386 --> 01:38:15.846
I don't want to miss another chance.
How is it possible?

01:38:15.932 --> 01:38:17.388
How can I do nothing about it?

01:38:17.475 --> 01:38:18.840
I've been asking myself...

01:38:18.935 --> 01:38:22.644
For 25 years and I've only been able
to come up with one answer.

01:38:22.730 --> 01:38:26.314
"Forget it, it was another lifetime.
It's over, don't ask."

01:38:26.401 --> 01:38:29.234
It wasn't another lifetime.
It was this one.

01:38:30.613 --> 01:38:32.069
It is this one.

01:38:32.615 --> 01:38:34.230
Now I want to understand.

01:38:34.325 --> 01:38:36.486
How can someone live an empty life?

01:38:36.577 --> 01:38:40.069
How do you live a life
full of nothing?

01:38:40.873 --> 01:38:42.283
How do you do it?

01:38:42.959 --> 01:38:45.826
A new part of the search starts here,

01:38:45.920 --> 01:38:49.287
a search they embark on together.

01:38:51.259 --> 01:38:55.252
Just like sandoval showed the way earlier,

01:38:56.931 --> 01:39:00.298
and this time Irene does.

01:39:01.269 --> 01:39:03.385
You see? That's his mother.

01:39:03.938 --> 01:39:07.977
Sir, we are required by law
to notify a change of address.

01:39:08.067 --> 01:39:11.525
It's not something we do because
we feel like it. Understand?

01:39:11.612 --> 01:39:13.398
- I do now.
- Morales, Ricardo.

01:39:13.489 --> 01:39:16.526
There's one, two... four, ma'am.

01:39:16.617 --> 01:39:18.448
Let's search by l.D. Number.

01:39:18.536 --> 01:39:21.118
- What's your first number?
- Three, what's yours?

01:39:22.081 --> 01:39:24.948
What do you care?
“What? Can'tl...?

01:39:25.042 --> 01:39:29.752
Here's a five and a six.
Morales, Ricardo Augustin.

01:39:30.465 --> 01:39:32.751
He changed addresses in 1975.

01:39:33.718 --> 01:39:35.504
Write this down, pata-pata.

01:39:57.074 --> 01:40:00.487
There was a new search for color
in this scene as well,

01:40:00.578 --> 01:40:06.744
a color that doesn't quite fit
in the present or the past.

01:40:07.210 --> 01:40:11.249
Although we still have color desaturation,

01:40:11.339 --> 01:40:15.924
there's a brown, earthy element
and an element of scorching sun

01:40:16.010 --> 01:40:17.500
that is much more prevalent.

01:40:17.595 --> 01:40:21.929
This will be even more apparent
when we see

01:40:22.016 --> 01:40:24.098
esposito leaving the morales situation.

01:40:28.022 --> 01:40:31.685
This is where we start
to insert little clues

01:40:33.236 --> 01:40:37.570
that don't attract attention in themselves,

01:40:37.657 --> 01:40:41.946
but make you feel
like something isn't quite right,

01:40:42.036 --> 01:40:44.618
including the film narrative.

01:40:44.705 --> 01:40:46.946
I'll explain when we get to them.

01:40:48.709 --> 01:40:50.916
A totally solitary place.

01:40:53.089 --> 01:40:56.877
There are no dogs,
which is strange for a farm.

01:40:57.802 --> 01:41:02.045
There are no dogs, although they could alert
someone to the presence of other people.

01:41:05.142 --> 01:41:08.509
The man we see in the distance
is carrying a tray of things,

01:41:08.604 --> 01:41:10.720
which could be strange, or not.

01:41:14.068 --> 01:41:15.808
- Quite a surprise.
- I know...

01:41:15.903 --> 01:41:19.066
We don't draw any attention
to the tray, of course.

01:41:20.741 --> 01:41:25.701
Morales is uncomfortable.
There's a constant tension

01:41:26.455 --> 01:41:31.540
between what he feels,
which is extreme danger,

01:41:31.627 --> 01:41:37.088
and the way he thinks he should appear,
which is like a man with no worries.

01:41:38.092 --> 01:41:42.586
What problem could cause this man
from that time to pay him a visit?

01:41:45.266 --> 01:41:48.133
What I was saying
about film narrative is coming up.

01:41:48.227 --> 01:41:50.343
There is no reason

01:41:51.647 --> 01:41:54.810
for the cut that's coming up here.

01:41:56.444 --> 01:41:58.605
Him drawing that curtain.

01:41:58.696 --> 01:42:00.937
No reason whatsoever.

01:42:03.784 --> 01:42:06.776
As viewers, we sense
that something strange just happened,

01:42:06.871 --> 01:42:10.864
but we can't understand what.

01:42:10.958 --> 01:42:14.041
It's just a hunch that
there was something odd

01:42:14.128 --> 01:42:16.289
about that cut, and then it passes.

01:42:17.173 --> 01:42:19.289
This will all come back, of course.

01:42:20.301 --> 01:42:23.213
There's always a branch nobody wants,
so here I am...

01:42:23.387 --> 01:42:25.127
With a promotion and everything.

01:42:25.473 --> 01:42:27.134
It seems incredible,

01:42:27.224 --> 01:42:31.092
but esposito hasn't even seen a picture
of Liliana coloto in 25 years.

01:42:32.271 --> 01:42:35.354
He's seeing her for the first time
after 25 years.

01:42:35.816 --> 01:42:37.147
Remember Liliana?

01:42:39.695 --> 01:42:41.651
He comes face to face with his memory.

01:42:44.742 --> 01:42:49.827
In the shot of the photo, we saw
some medical books that we'll come back to.

01:42:50.873 --> 01:42:52.613
Still here.

01:42:53.584 --> 01:42:55.415
No, I mean single...

01:42:55.503 --> 01:42:57.664
- Married...
- No.

01:42:57.838 --> 01:42:59.078
No, really.

01:42:59.173 --> 01:43:01.880
I think I just... at that point...

01:43:01.967 --> 01:43:05.676
Morales is obviously trying to be
as good-natured as possible.

01:43:05.763 --> 01:43:08.755
He has no reason to be anything but.

01:43:08.849 --> 01:43:14.890
Or at least esposito shouldn't know
that he has a reason.

01:43:15.022 --> 01:43:16.512
Yeah, for a while.

01:43:18.025 --> 01:43:19.561
But it didn't work.

01:43:20.069 --> 01:43:22.651
I don't know if it was me...

01:43:24.115 --> 01:43:26.651
It's complicated.

01:43:33.207 --> 01:43:37.371
This scene is set up like a cockfight.

01:43:39.880 --> 01:43:41.290
We see two competitors...

01:43:41.382 --> 01:43:44.590
We see... we are esposito,

01:43:44.677 --> 01:43:49.137
studying the person we want
to get certain information from.

01:43:51.684 --> 01:43:53.470
And we'll stay with him

01:43:55.563 --> 01:43:57.679
in a sequence with almost no cuts.

01:43:57.773 --> 01:44:00.560
Incredible work by Miguel caram here,

01:44:01.736 --> 01:44:04.398
operating the camera. He's the cameraman.

01:44:05.114 --> 01:44:08.982
Everything you're about to see
was filmed with a hand-held camera.

01:44:09.076 --> 01:44:11.533
You'll see cuts
to a couple of reverse angle shots,

01:44:11.620 --> 01:44:14.657
but the entire sequence was filmed
in one take,

01:44:14.749 --> 01:44:18.583
from when morales is reading
to when they finish by the door.

01:44:25.426 --> 01:44:28.759
We go with him. We're on the attack.

01:44:30.306 --> 01:44:32.422
- How do you know?
- I just read it.

01:44:32.600 --> 01:44:35.012
- They found your friend.
- Oh, right.

01:44:36.729 --> 01:44:38.765
He's closing him in gradually.

01:44:39.607 --> 01:44:40.607
No.

01:44:41.150 --> 01:44:43.266
My coworker at the courts.

01:44:45.404 --> 01:44:47.520
They came looking for me,
didn't find me...

01:44:47.948 --> 01:44:49.484
And let him have it.

01:44:49.950 --> 01:44:51.360
Bastards.

01:44:54.622 --> 01:44:55.782
Gomez was never found, right?

01:44:55.831 --> 01:44:58.664
While editing, I studied the possibilities

01:44:58.751 --> 01:45:02.289
of not making that cut we just saw,
and simply stopping on him.

01:45:05.674 --> 01:45:08.040
I decided to leave it.

01:45:08.135 --> 01:45:10.376
I decided to let viewers see

01:45:10.471 --> 01:45:15.010
that moment of weighing how to proceed...

01:45:19.063 --> 01:45:20.599
It was 25 years ago, esposito.

01:45:20.689 --> 01:45:21.958
I was sure you wouldn't be able to.

01:45:21.982 --> 01:45:26.191
But the entire scene, what we're seeing
now, was a continuation of the last one,

01:45:26.278 --> 01:45:28.269
the camera was approaching with esposito.

01:45:30.241 --> 01:45:31.526
Forget it.

01:45:39.458 --> 01:45:41.995
That was the camera moving backward,

01:45:44.755 --> 01:45:47.371
but we get that sense

01:45:47.466 --> 01:45:52.301
of two opponents in a cockfight
coming together and pulling apart.

01:45:53.264 --> 01:45:55.505
I don't know what you want me to say.

01:45:55.599 --> 01:45:58.432
You didn't care
the guy got a free ride.

01:45:58.519 --> 01:45:59.759
There was nothing I could do.

01:46:01.981 --> 01:46:05.769
You spent a year looking for the guy,
they let him go and you do nothing?

01:46:05.860 --> 01:46:08.727
I wasted a year looking for him
and they let him go!

01:46:08.821 --> 01:46:10.311
- What can I do?
- That's it?

01:46:10.447 --> 01:46:12.207
- Yes!
- The rest of your life behind a desk?

01:46:12.491 --> 01:46:14.135
Look who's talking.
You're better than I am.

01:46:14.159 --> 01:46:18.869
He closes in on him again. And every time
esposito ups the pressure and approaches,

01:46:18.956 --> 01:46:20.196
he escapes.

01:46:21.500 --> 01:46:22.831
And he approaches him again.

01:46:23.460 --> 01:46:26.372
Your love for that woman...
I never saw it again.

01:46:26.839 --> 01:46:27.919
In anybody.

01:46:28.549 --> 01:46:29.549
Coming closer every time.

01:46:29.592 --> 01:46:30.877
Nobody.

01:46:31.510 --> 01:46:32.716
Ever.

01:46:36.974 --> 01:46:38.714
Get out of my house.

01:46:40.436 --> 01:46:41.892
He pulls back again.

01:46:42.146 --> 01:46:43.636
Right now, please.

01:46:45.232 --> 01:46:47.518
It's my life, not yours.

01:46:48.193 --> 01:46:51.276
He failed. He needs to
rethink his strategy.

01:46:54.742 --> 01:46:58.280
Change his angle of attack and with it...

01:47:00.915 --> 01:47:02.325
Getting old, that's it.

01:47:03.417 --> 01:47:05.373
We change the camera angle.

01:47:05.753 --> 01:47:07.038
That might be it.

01:47:12.927 --> 01:47:14.918
I couldn't stop thinking about it.

01:47:15.012 --> 01:47:16.673
Go dwell on it at home.

01:47:29.777 --> 01:47:33.895
It seems like he's pulling back slowly,
but instead of going out the door...

01:47:34.615 --> 01:47:36.230
Gomez didn't kill sandoval.

01:47:36.325 --> 01:47:37.531
He attacks again.

01:47:38.285 --> 01:47:39.400
So?

01:47:40.120 --> 01:47:41.906
He knew us both.

01:47:42.206 --> 01:47:45.198
If he'd been there,
he'd have waited for me.

01:47:49.505 --> 01:47:51.211
There's something...

01:47:52.007 --> 01:47:54.089
I had a couple of photos at home,
of myself.

01:47:54.843 --> 01:47:56.299
When sandoval got killed...

01:47:56.553 --> 01:48:00.796
We gradually close the gap between them.

01:48:01.809 --> 01:48:03.640
Nothing else had been touched.

01:48:04.853 --> 01:48:06.138
I thought...

01:48:08.399 --> 01:48:09.559
I think...

01:48:28.127 --> 01:48:29.788
Are you esposito?

01:48:34.216 --> 01:48:35.376
Did you hear what I said...

01:48:35.467 --> 01:48:38.709
We'll never know if this really happened
this way either,

01:48:40.305 --> 01:48:43.513
whether esposito is imagining it

01:48:43.600 --> 01:48:45.932
or it's what he needs to believe.

01:48:46.603 --> 01:48:47.843
Answer me.

01:48:50.858 --> 01:48:52.439
Where are you going?

01:48:53.861 --> 01:48:55.351
- Where are you going?
- Here.

01:48:55.446 --> 01:48:57.186
It doesn't really matter anyway.

01:48:59.033 --> 01:49:01.695
I'm going to put on a record.
It's okay.

01:49:03.746 --> 01:49:05.077
A record?

01:49:05.372 --> 01:49:06.703
Listen to me.

01:49:07.791 --> 01:49:10.407
Are you esposito or not?

01:49:17.676 --> 01:49:19.212
Yes, I am.

01:49:53.754 --> 01:49:55.585
Morales obviously didn't know about this.

01:49:55.672 --> 01:49:58.755
Now they've both lost a loved one.

01:50:00.552 --> 01:50:05.342
Without evaluating the degree of affection

01:50:05.432 --> 01:50:09.016
one can feel for a beloved woman
or a friend,

01:50:09.103 --> 01:50:10.934
this is reflected

01:50:12.147 --> 01:50:14.433
in the two of them sharing the frame.

01:50:14.525 --> 01:50:17.517
One is a continuation of the other,
there's no distance between them.

01:50:19.279 --> 01:50:23.522
We used a happy accident here,

01:50:24.159 --> 01:50:29.279
seeing esposito's eyes
through morales' glasses.

01:50:30.874 --> 01:50:33.616
Memories are all we end up with.

01:50:33.710 --> 01:50:35.496
At least pick the nice ones.

01:50:38.549 --> 01:50:40.210
But there's one thing...

01:50:40.300 --> 01:50:42.336
I know I'll never forget.

01:50:43.679 --> 01:50:46.796
The last thing Pablo said to me
the night they killed him.

01:50:46.890 --> 01:50:49.472
"Don't worry, Benjamin.

01:50:49.560 --> 01:50:51.266
We'll catch that son of a bitch."

01:50:53.605 --> 01:50:55.141
And I will.

01:50:57.317 --> 01:50:59.103
If he's alive, I will.

01:51:05.826 --> 01:51:09.239
Morales' eye tells us much more

01:51:09.955 --> 01:51:14.039
than any words we could shout, or what
seeing his whole face or body could reveal.

01:51:25.637 --> 01:51:29.550
And morales does esposito a favor,
the favor he owed him.

01:51:31.685 --> 01:51:34.142
He gives him an "answer,"

01:51:35.272 --> 01:51:37.308
and frees him from the whole dilemma.

01:51:40.903 --> 01:51:46.648
And in a way, he says, or thinks to himself,
"there's only room for two in this prison."

01:52:16.521 --> 01:52:21.390
The next shot is one of the most complex
in the movie in terms of visual effects.

01:52:23.862 --> 01:52:26.899
We had no control over the trains,
of course.

01:52:26.990 --> 01:52:29.857
We had to shoot
when the train was going by.

01:52:29.952 --> 01:52:32.364
The conditions weren't precise.

01:52:32.454 --> 01:52:35.287
The sky you're about to see is fake.

01:52:39.253 --> 01:52:43.917
At the factory you see in the background,

01:52:44.007 --> 01:52:49.593
there were a number of modern
electrical poles that we had to erase.

01:52:50.138 --> 01:52:53.346
By erasing them, we also had to erase
the reeds behind morales.

01:52:53.433 --> 01:52:56.846
So the reeds you see now are animated.

01:52:56.937 --> 01:52:59.053
They're computer-generated.

01:52:59.147 --> 01:53:03.561
The train was modern,
so we had to create one from that era.

01:53:04.236 --> 01:53:05.851
Those three brief shots you saw

01:53:05.946 --> 01:53:09.530
were some of the most important
and laborious in terms of visual effects.

01:53:14.288 --> 01:53:16.495
Here, when morales leans forward,

01:53:16.581 --> 01:53:20.995
we start to give full meaning

01:53:22.170 --> 01:53:24.832
to the expression, "the eyes speak."

01:53:24.923 --> 01:53:26.333
Was it worth it?

01:53:28.051 --> 01:53:29.541
Forget about it.

01:53:29.928 --> 01:53:31.668
Forget it.

01:53:32.597 --> 01:53:33.928
Who cares?

01:53:34.808 --> 01:53:36.139
My wife is dead.

01:53:36.226 --> 01:53:38.558
We start with...

01:53:40.480 --> 01:53:46.396
Esposito's hazy shoulder
obscures morales' mouth,

01:53:46.486 --> 01:53:48.602
leaving only the eyes.

01:53:50.532 --> 01:53:52.193
Forget about it, trust me.

01:53:54.244 --> 01:53:56.610
You'll end up with only memories.

01:54:01.126 --> 01:54:02.662
I owed you one, right?

01:54:05.130 --> 01:54:06.711
Now we're even.

01:54:24.483 --> 01:54:29.102
The train sequence we saw earlier
was the second hardest to edit.

01:54:29.196 --> 01:54:31.278
This was the hardest.

01:54:31.365 --> 01:54:37.031
Not only for visual,
rhythmic and editing reasons,

01:54:37.120 --> 01:54:41.113
but also in terms of how we rationed
the information.

01:54:41.208 --> 01:54:46.669
I have to thank Camilo antolini,
who edited all my past movies,

01:54:46.755 --> 01:54:49.622
for solving this
with the motif of the four shots.

01:54:49.716 --> 01:54:52.458
The repetition of those four shots.

01:54:52.552 --> 01:54:56.841
Morales said repeatedly,
"they won't get me anywhere."

01:54:59.559 --> 01:55:00.559
Ciao.

01:55:03.313 --> 01:55:05.850
It wasn't another lifetime.
It was this one.

01:55:06.024 --> 01:55:08.891
A guy can do anything to be different.

01:55:09.694 --> 01:55:11.275
What would four bullets get me?

01:55:11.446 --> 01:55:13.562
But there's one thing he can't change.
Not him...

01:55:13.740 --> 01:55:15.401
And the four shots again.

01:55:26.837 --> 01:55:30.705
At this point,
we didn't have to know what happened,

01:55:31.842 --> 01:55:33.173
but we could start setting it up.

01:55:33.260 --> 01:55:38.596
Rationing that information was the hardest
part of this scene and the movie.

01:55:39.266 --> 01:55:44.135
And creating that mood of...
Great sound work here.

01:55:45.147 --> 01:55:47.934
The scorching sun here again.

01:56:01.413 --> 01:56:05.577
Basically, the challenge is to give
a lot of information

01:56:05.667 --> 01:56:07.783
while maintaining a strong mood.

01:56:07.878 --> 01:56:13.544
In general, information and mood don't mix.

01:56:21.766 --> 01:56:22.926
How do you do it?

01:56:33.320 --> 01:56:37.780
The music in the last part of the movie
is excellent.

01:56:37.866 --> 01:56:41.358
It began when esposito was in the car

01:56:41.453 --> 01:56:46.573
and will go on until he writes the note,

01:56:46.666 --> 01:56:48.202
until he corrects the "I fear."

01:56:48.293 --> 01:56:51.251
It's nine and a half minutes
of uninterrupted music

01:56:51.338 --> 01:56:53.795
that spans all moods, from...

01:56:53.882 --> 01:56:58.216
I wouldn't say suspenseful music,
but rather gothic,

01:57:03.183 --> 01:57:06.926
captivating,
because right now it's hypnotic.

01:57:07.020 --> 01:57:10.262
It's propelling us forward, it has drive.

01:57:11.525 --> 01:57:15.268
And it has dramatic changes in key,
I'll tell you when,

01:57:16.947 --> 01:57:18.608
and tone.

01:57:21.535 --> 01:57:22.695
I fucked the shit out of her!

01:57:22.786 --> 01:57:23.821
What retribution?

01:57:23.912 --> 01:57:29.407
It's a subtle, excellent arrangement
by federico jusid.

01:57:29.501 --> 01:57:30.686
It's as if his wife's death...

01:57:30.710 --> 01:57:32.575
Just left him there,
stuck in time forever.

01:57:36.341 --> 01:57:37.797
My wife is dead.

01:57:38.009 --> 01:57:41.467
Your friend is dead.
Gomez is dead too. They're all dead.

01:57:43.682 --> 01:57:45.513
They'd give him an injection...

01:57:45.600 --> 01:57:46.840
And he'd take a nap.

01:57:47.143 --> 01:57:48.724
Nobody, Benjamin.

01:57:49.771 --> 01:57:51.557
Let him grow old.

01:57:52.232 --> 01:57:54.723
Live a life full of nothing.

01:57:55.110 --> 01:57:56.691
How did you start over?

01:57:56.903 --> 01:57:58.985
That was 25 years ago.

01:58:00.073 --> 01:58:02.780
25 years, esposito.

01:58:03.743 --> 01:58:04.983
Forget about it.

01:58:06.955 --> 01:58:10.322
When it seems like the music will rise,
it fades.

01:58:12.002 --> 01:58:15.915
As the music fades,
we move forward, almost physically.

01:58:16.548 --> 01:58:19.255
We stand up in our seat,
we want to see more,

01:58:19.342 --> 01:58:21.549
we want to see better,
we want to hear more.

01:58:22.262 --> 01:58:23.752
We're alert.

01:58:48.705 --> 01:58:50.491
And the music fades even more.

01:59:30.163 --> 01:59:34.406
In one of the first drafts of the script,

01:59:36.461 --> 01:59:41.672
when Gomez saw esposito,
he started screaming wildly,

01:59:41.758 --> 01:59:46.092
"someone came, they found me.
Get me out of here."

01:59:46.179 --> 01:59:49.342
And he kept screaming as esposito left.

01:59:49.432 --> 01:59:52.970
It was aida bortnik
who pointed out the error in that.

01:59:53.061 --> 01:59:56.269
She told us that after 25 years,

01:59:56.356 --> 01:59:59.894
this character would have lost
that attitude long ago,

02:00:01.361 --> 02:00:03.101
he was a broken character.

02:00:03.196 --> 02:00:07.280
She said he should ask for a favor,
the most banal favor possible.

02:00:07.367 --> 02:00:10.700
Tell him at least to talk to me.

02:00:18.420 --> 02:00:20.832
She said this would be much more powerful,
and it was.

02:00:28.722 --> 02:00:30.053
Please.

02:01:13.141 --> 02:01:14.347
You said life.

02:01:29.657 --> 02:01:35.277
How do we go
from a tragic scene like this one

02:01:35.371 --> 02:01:39.865
to the final scene in the movie,
which is practically a love scene?

02:01:39.959 --> 02:01:43.918
Modulatory Bridges were needed here again.

02:01:44.005 --> 02:01:46.041
You'll notice them in the music,

02:01:46.132 --> 02:01:50.546
the direction
and even the dramatic composition.

02:01:50.637 --> 02:01:54.880
The cemetery scene, which is coming up,

02:01:54.974 --> 02:02:00.264
is a scene
where both storylines come together.

02:02:00.897 --> 02:02:04.105
There's the death of sandoval,

02:02:05.401 --> 02:02:07.983
which occurred in the detective story,

02:02:09.864 --> 02:02:14.278
but esposito's visit to sandoval
is part of the movie's human storyline.

02:02:14.369 --> 02:02:16.860
It's a scene of transition.

02:02:18.581 --> 02:02:22.073
This strong change in the visual code

02:02:22.168 --> 02:02:24.409
to a white place colored by flowers.

02:02:24.504 --> 02:02:28.747
When we opened the scene with the flowers, it
looked like we were in a field of flowers,

02:02:28.842 --> 02:02:30.503
but it was just a florist's.

02:02:30.593 --> 02:02:32.754
Pay attention to the music here,

02:02:32.846 --> 02:02:38.261
the way it changes subtly
when he sees the note "I fear."

02:02:47.193 --> 02:02:48.808
I fear

02:02:58.371 --> 02:03:01.158
I love you

02:03:01.374 --> 02:03:03.865
it's brilliant.

02:03:03.960 --> 02:03:06.417
That change is incredible

02:03:06.504 --> 02:03:09.667
and it enables us
to perform an impossible balancing act.

02:03:19.559 --> 02:03:21.925
- Is she in?
- Yeah, in her office.

02:03:25.648 --> 02:03:31.314
The movie doesn't say what esposito does
with what he learns at morales' house.

02:03:33.156 --> 02:03:37.741
It's not necessary at this moment,
for this story,

02:03:37.827 --> 02:03:40.534
but we can guess what he does later.

02:03:40.622 --> 02:03:44.240
We know his character well enough.

02:03:45.460 --> 02:03:50.671
We intentionally didn't
show it in the movie

02:03:50.757 --> 02:03:52.588
so we could spark that debate.

02:03:52.675 --> 02:03:57.169
We thought that if the question people
asked at the café after the theater was,

02:03:57.263 --> 02:04:01.006
"what would esposito do,
knowing that Gomez is in that cell?"

02:04:02.101 --> 02:04:05.935
This question would quickly become,
"what would I do?"

02:04:09.233 --> 02:04:13.101
And that's what we wanted to ask
in the movie.

02:04:14.030 --> 02:04:15.315
Shut the door.

02:04:21.329 --> 02:04:23.035
I hope you enjoyed it.

02:04:28.294 --> 02:04:31.411
The secret in their eyes
